<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1229,2010]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,1877,1901]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished from other species of the genus by the unique paired apical processes of the aedeagus, which are approximately triangular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="58" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1229,2010]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,1949,1973]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<taxonomicName box="[937,999,1949,1973]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Limassolla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rutila">
<emphasis box="[937,999,1949,1973]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">rutila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, which refers to the forewing with a prominent orange red pattern (marked with short oblique dashes as in 
<figureCitation box="[935,1015,1985,2009]" captionStart="FIGURES 28 – 37" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1637,1660]" captionTargetBox="[164,1434,197,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,179,1616]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 28 – 37. Limassolla rutila sp. nov. 28. Head and thorax, dorsal view. 29. Fore wing. 30. Hindwing. 31. Abdominal apodemes. 32. Pygofer lobe, lateral view. 33. Subgenital plate. 34. Style. 35. Aedeagus, lateral view. 36. Aedeagus ventral view. 37. Connective, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279419/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[986,1015,1985,2009]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58" value="29.0">29</number>
</figureCitation>
) around the claval suture.
</paragraph>
